A high pass filter was applied to reduce background noise below 1500 Hz by 12dB. Habitat is a 30 acre stand of upland oak/hickory forest surrounded by light urban development. Bird began calling moments before a light rain began. Recording was begun within 30 sec of the beginning of vocalizations and recorded the entire duration of the subsequent continuous vocalizations until the bird became silent. Recorded with an Olympus LS-10.

recordings.rmk: The recording was modified to remove extraneous noise, people talking, etc, as much as possible. The habitat was an open forested area near some suburbs and a road. There's a grassy field overlooking Lake Champlain. Additionally, a bike path goes through a riparian forest with typical Vermont plants such as cottonwoods, maples, buckthorn, sumac, ferns, etc. I decided to mark this as both "song" and "call" since I've heard conflicting things on whether or not flycatchers have songs, properly speaking. I'm not sure if we saw this particular individual, though I don't believe we did. I definitely didn't, though. I know we saw at least one other individual along the path, though, and heard some others. Check out [this eBird list](https://ebird.org/checklist/S56605170) for more info on that particular trip. The weather was cloudy, as I recall, but otherwise the trip was an unremarkable midday May outing.

recordings.rmk: Time and date estimated; Early in the field season in 2010, as migrant birds were settling into their breeding territories, I recorded this newly settled great crested flycatcher 'singing' from a prominent perch. These vocalizations appeared as a song to me because of the cadence is steady and distinct, unlike the calls of great crested flycatchers I am more familiar with. This was the first time I became aware of the song of this non-melodic species. Great Crested bred on this territory later in the season.  Riparian deciduous forest; filtered noise 800 Hz and below
